narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I did not develop many skills and knowledge from this course. I have already taken this math class, so I know most of the material already but haven't gained a better knowledge of it.
I developed better mathematic abilities, as well as learned new techniques for solving problems.
It was a good review of high school calculus. I don't feel as though I gained any skills.
I developed the skills necessary to take Calc II.
Basics of calculus.
I learned how to use peer tutoring as a resource and how to find resources outside the classroom when class isn't working.
I learned the fundamentals of differential calculus. It was a great way to fill in the gaps from calculus in high school and I feel much more prepared for integral calculus.
I learned how to approach difficult problems and learned the proofs and reasonings behind why certain mathematical theorems work.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I would have preferred a large combined lecture, the atmosphere of the sections was often stifling and there is also an imbalance across the teaching fellows.
The problem sets were hard and made me think. I thought there should be more practice material for the midterms and final.

I feel as though the curriculum was very well structured and flowed quite nicely.

However, I felt as though the instructors were not given enough training and did not necessarily have the capabilities to teach such a structured course.

In my opinion the class moved a bit too slowly. We spent a lot of time in class just listening to a lecture-like explanation of theorems. I think it could be helpful to have more exercises and examples to help us understand better and help the class move along more smoothly.
The structure of the class was not very helpful. Topics weren't always clearly explained even when clarification was requested. I often turned to peers or peer tutors for math support.

This course has strengths in problem-solving. For problems not directly related to calculus, but still used calculus, it was interesting to learn the processes to solve these problems. Additionally, although there was not an emphasis on proofs, it was helpful to have proofs spread out throughout the lessons. There's not much that can be done to improve this course.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: If you need a math credit, sure.
I think this course was fine overall, so I would recommend this course for a student that needs to take the class. I would not recommend the teacher.

I would not, since I find that although the content and structure was there, there was a severe lacking in the teaching aspect that made it very difficult to learn in the classroom without outside sources (I learned more in the review sessions for the final than in the entire semester long course).
If you don't understand beginner's calculus, you should definitely take the course but if not definitely try your best to place out of it.
Yes, I would recommend this course to students that feel unconfident about their calculus ability and are unsure whether they would like to continue calculus.
I would recommend the course to students who have not taken Calculus AB before, since it is a good introduction to maths taught at university.
